04965nam a22005415i 9780226797977DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021007569  a97802267979777 a10.7208/chicago/97802267979772doi  a(DE-B1597)600753  a(OCoLC)1264469669  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK516b.D427 2021 4aJK516 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a352.23/509731 aDearborn, John A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPower Shifts :bCongress and Presidential Representation /cJohn A. Dearborn. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b1 halftone, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Studies in American Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface: Rethinking a Political Truism -- t1. Introduction: Legislating Presidential Power -- t2. Ideas and Political Development -- tPART I. Institutional Choice: Creating the Institutional Presidency, 1910– 49 -- t3. Presidential Budgeting -- t4. Presidential Economic Policymaking -- t5. Presidential Reorganization Authority -- t6. Presidential National Security Authority -- tPART II. Institutional Durability: Reconsidering the Institutional Presidency, 1970– 84 -- t7. Congressional Pushback against Presidential Budgeting -- t8. Congressional Pushback against Presidential Economic Policymaking -- t9. Congressional Pushback against Presidential Reorganization Authority -- t10. Congressional Pushback against Presidential National Security Authority -- t11. Conclusion: Ideas and the Politics of Adaptability -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThat the president uniquely represents the national interest is a political truism, yet this idea has been transformational, shaping the efforts of Congress to remake the presidency and testing the adaptability of American constitutional government. The emergence of the modern presidency in the first half of the twentieth century transformed the American government. But surprisingly, presidents were not the primary driving force of this change—Congress was. Through a series of statutes, lawmakers endorsed presidential leadership in the legislative process and augmented the chief executive’s organizational capacities. But why did Congress grant presidents this power? In Power Shifts, John A. Dearborn shows that legislators acted on the idea that the president was the best representative of the national interest. Congress subordinated its own claims to stand as the nation’s primary representative institution and designed reforms that assumed the president was the superior steward of all the people. In the process, Congress recast the nation’s chief executive as its chief representative. As Dearborn demonstrates, the full extent to which Congress’s reforms rested on the idea of presidential representation was revealed when that notion’s validity was thrown into doubt. In the 1970s, Congress sought to restore its place in a rebalanced system, but legislators also found that their earlier success at institutional reinvention constrained their efforts to reclaim authority. Chronicling the evolving relationship between the presidency and Congress across a range of policy areas, Power Shifts exposes a fundamental dilemma in an otherwise proud tradition of constitutional adaptation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aExecutive powerzUnited States. 0aPresidentszUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aadaptability, american, authority, century, constitutional, country, executive, government, institution, lawmakers, leadership, legislative, national, policy, political, presid